    "instruction": "Load metric.csv, trace.csv, log.csv, and error_logs.csv into memory and parse their timestamp columns as UTC datetimes. For each file, provide a compact summary: total row count, earliest and latest timestamp (as UTC datetimes), list of distinct cmdb_id values, and list of distinct KPI/feature names (use kpi_name for metric.csv, trace_name for trace.csv, log_name for log.csv). Additionally: \n- For metric.csv: compute per (cmdb_id, kpi_name) global P95 value using the full available series, and return the top 20 (cmdb_id, kpi_name) entries ranked by number of samples with their sample count and P95 value. \n- For trace.csv and log.csv: return the top 20 distinct (cmdb_id, trace_name) and (cmdb_id, log_name) combinations respectively with their sample counts. \n- For error_logs.csv: return total row count, distinct cmdb_id list, and up to 10 sample rows (limited columns: timestamp, cmdb_id, message). \nLimit all returned rows/lists to at most 20 entries each. Do not print full raw time series."
}

{
    "analysis": "From the previous step we loaded and summarized all telemetry. Metric/trace/log data cover 2024-01-23 12:27 — 12:51 UTC (which lies inside the incident window 2024-01-23 12:24:34 — 12:54:34). A per-(cmdb_id,kpi_name) global P95 was already computed across full metric series. error_logs.csv is empty so no error log clues. Next we must use metric anomaly detection to narrow candidate faulty components before using traces/logs for localization. To detect both spikes and drops, we should compute global P95 and P05 for each (cmdb_id,kpi_name), then flag anomaly points within the incident window where value >= P95 (spike) or value <= P05 (drop). Aggregate by (cmdb_id,kpi_name) and return compact summary (counts, earliest anomaly time, extremes, thresholds) limited to top candidates.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using metric.csv, perform the following steps in one run: 1) Compute global P95 and P05 for every (cmdb_id, kpi_name) using the full available series (do NOT filter by incident window for these percentiles). 2) Parse timestamps as UTC and filter metric rows to the incident window [2024-01-23 12:24:34 UTC, 2024-01-23 12:54:34 UTC] (inclusive). 3) Join the filtered rows with the computed P95/P05 per (cmdb_id,kpi_name) and flag a row as an anomaly if value >= P95 or value <= P05. 4) Aggregate anomalies by (cmdb_id, kpi_name) producing: cmdb_id, kpi_name, sample_count_in_window (total rows in window for this series), anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp_utc, max_value_in_window, min_value_in_window, p95, p05. 5) Return up to the top 20 aggregated rows with anomaly_count > 0, sorted by anomaly_count desc then max_value_in_window desc. Limit all returned rows to at most 20. Do not print full raw series — only the aggregated summary columns specified."
}

{
    "analysis": "You computed global P95/P05 across all metric series and flagged anomalies in the incident window. The top anomalies are dominated by database/mysql/mongo socket and mem series where every sample in the window equals the global percentile (likely constant series or small sample effects). None of those initial top anomalies were explicitly the five candidate services listed for root-cause localization (ts-auth-service, ts-order-service, ts-route-service, ts-train-service, ts-travel-service). According to the workflow, we must now narrow the search to the provided candidate components: compute their global thresholds, detect anomalous KPI behavior in the incident window for these specific services, and then use traces/logs to localize the root cause. Next we should focus metric anomaly summaries for only those five candidate services to see if any show consecutive anomalies; if no clear metric fault appears, we will inspect traces calling/being called by these services and then logs for error/row_count anomalies.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "For the target candidate services only (cmdb_id in ['ts-auth-service','ts-order-service','ts-route-service','ts-train-service','ts-travel-service']), do the following in one run: 1) From metric.csv compute global P95 and P05 per (cmdb_id, kpi_name) using the full available series. 2) Parse timestamps as UTC and filter metric rows to the incident window [2024-01-23 12:24:34 UTC, 2024-01-23 12:54:34 UTC]. 3) For the filtered rows, flag anomalies where value >= P95 or value <= P05. 4) Aggregate anomalies by (cmdb_id, kpi_name) and return: cmdb_id, kpi_name, sample_count_in_window, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp_utc, max_value_in_window, min_value_in_window, p95, p05. 5) Return only rows with anomaly_count > 0, sorted by anomaly_count desc then max_value_in_window desc, limited to top 20. Also return a short summary count of how many of the five candidate services had at least one anomalous KPI in the window."
}

{
    "analysis": "You computed metric anomalies for the five candidate services and found that all five show some anomalous KPIs in the incident window. Most anomalies are small-tail deviations (anomaly_count = 4) on mem/diskio/socket/cpu/workload, while ts-order-service and ts-travel-service have a constant 'error' KPI of 0.0 flagged (artifact). According to the workflow, we now need trace analysis to (1) determine call relationships between these candidate services during the incident window and (2) identify which faulty service is the most downstream faulty service in traces. Traces can also reveal whether latency/error_rate spikes align with metric faults and help pick the root-cause service among multiple service-level anomalies. Therefore the next step is to scan trace.csv for trace series that involve any of the five candidate services (match service name in trace_name or cmdb_id), compute global P95/P05 per trace series using the full series, then filter traces to the incident window and flag trace anomalies (value >= P95 or <= P05). Aggregate compactly to show where traces show abnormal latency/error_rate/row_count, earliest anomaly time, and severity.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "In trace.csv: 1) Compute global P95 and P05 per (cmdb_id, trace_name) using the full available series (do NOT filter by window for thresholds). 2) Identify trace rows WHERE trace_name contains any of these service substrings: 'ts-auth-service','ts-order-service','ts-route-service','ts-train-service','ts-travel-service' OR cmdb_id is one of those five services. 3) Parse timestamps as UTC and filter the identified rows to the incident window [2024-01-23 12:24:34 UTC, 2024-01-23 12:54:34 UTC]. 4) Flag anomalies where value >= P95 or value <= P05. 5) Aggregate anomalies by (cmdb_id, trace_name) returning: cmdb_id, trace_name, sample_count_in_window, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp_utc, max_value_in_window, min_value_in_window, p95, p05. 6) Return only rows with anomaly_count > 0, sorted by anomaly_count desc then max_value_in_window desc, limited to top 20. Also return the count of distinct (cmdb_id, trace_name) series examined and the count that had anomalies."
}

{
    "analysis": "Previous steps:\n- Loaded metric/trace/log data covering the incident window (12:27–12:51 UTC), computed global thresholds, and ran metric anomaly detection for all services and for the five candidate services. Metrics show all five candidates have some anomalous KPIs in the window — mostly small-tail deviations (anomaly_count = 4) on mem/diskio/socket/cpu/workload; ts-order-service and ts-travel-service show a constant 'error' KPI of 0.0 (artifact). The earliest metric anomalies are around 2024-01-23 12:27:00 UTC (auth mem earliest at 12:31:00).\n- Trace analysis for the five candidates covered 208 trace series; many trace.error_rate series are constant zeros, producing trivial anomalies (sample_count=25, anomaly_count=25) — not a useful signal. Traces therefore did not clearly single out a downstream faulty service because error_rate instrumentation appears constant-zero across many series.\n- No entries in error_logs.csv.\nWhat can be derived so far: metrics point to small resource deviations across multiple candidate services (mem/diskio/socket/cpu/workload). Traces do not provide a clean downstream-fault signal due to many constant-zero error_rate series. The next logical step is focused log analysis for the five candidate services to see whether log.error_count or log.row_count show abnormal behavior during the incident window that correlates with metric anomalies and can indicate service-level failure (e.g., sudden drops in row_count or spikes in error_count).",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using log.csv, do the following in one run: 1) Compute global P95 and P05 per (cmdb_id, log_name) using the full available series (do NOT filter by window for thresholds). 2) Parse timestamps as UTC and filter log rows to the incident window [2024-01-23 12:24:34 UTC, 2024-01-23 12:54:34 UTC]. 3) Restrict to the five candidate services: cmdb_id in ['ts-auth-service','ts-order-service','ts-route-service','ts-train-service','ts-travel-service']. 4) Flag rows as anomalies where value >= P95 or value <= P05. 5) Aggregate anomalies by (cmdb_id, log_name) and return: cmdb_id, log_name, sample_count_in_window, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp_utc, max_value_in_window, min_value_in_window, p95, p05. 6) Return only rows with anomaly_count > 0, sorted by anomaly_count desc then max_value_in_window desc, limited to top 20. Also return the count of distinct candidate services that had at least one log anomaly."
}

{
    "analysis": "You examined metrics, traces, and logs. Metrics show small-tail resource deviations on all five candidate services (mem/diskio/socket/cpu/workload with anomaly_count=4) and constant-zero 'error' KPIs for ts-order and ts-travel (artifact). Logs show log.row_count drops (anomaly_count=4) for ts-travel, ts-route, ts-order, ts-auth (ts-train had no log anomalies). Traces were dominated by constant-zero error_rate series producing trivial anomaly flags; that made trace.error_rate not useful. The remaining meaningful signals are row_count drops in logs and small but consistent metric deviations starting ~2024-01-23 12:27:00 UTC. To localize the root cause among multiple service-level anomalies we must find which candidate appears as the most downstream faulty service in call traces and which trace endpoints show the largest throughput drop or latency increase. Thus we should analyze trace row_count and duration series that reference the candidate services (trace.to_ts-*/trace.from_ts-* with row_count/duration metrics), compute global thresholds, filter to the incident window, and quantify severity per trace endpoint (e.g., percent drop in row_count compared to P95 or percent increase in duration compared to P95). Return a compact ranked list of the most severe trace-level faults (top 20) with earliest timestamps so we can pick the downstream faulty service.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From trace.csv: 1) Select trace series where trace_name contains 'to_ts-' or 'from_ts-' AND contains either 'row_count' or 'duration' (duration_mean or duration_p95), and where the referenced service substring (the token after 'to_ts-' or 'from_ts-' up to the next '.') matches any of the five candidates: ['ts-auth-service','ts-order-service','ts-route-service','ts-train-service','ts-travel-service']. 2) For each selected (cmdb_id, trace_name) compute global P95 and P05 using the full series (do NOT filter by window for thresholds). 3) Parse timestamps as UTC and filter rows to the incident window [2024-01-23 12:24:34 UTC, 2024-01-23 12:54:34 UTC]. 4) For each series, compute: sample_count_in_window, anomaly_count (value >= P95 or <= P05), earliest_anomaly_timestamp_utc, max_value_in_window, min_value_in_window, p95, p05. Additionally compute a severity score: if the metric is a 'row_count' and min_value_in_window < p05 then severity = (p95 - min_value_in_window) / max(1, p95) (a relative drop); if the metric is a 'duration' and max_value_in_window > p95 then severity = (max_value_in_window - p95) / max(1, p95) (a relative increase); otherwise severity = 0. 5) Return aggregated rows with anomaly_count > 0, limited to top 20 sorted by severity desc then anomaly_count desc. Include columns: cmdb_id, trace_name, referenced_service (extracted), metric_type ('row_count' or 'duration_mean'/'duration_p95'), sample_count_in_window, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp_utc, max_value_in_window, min_value_in_window, p95, p05, severity. Also return counts: number of series examined and number with anomalies."
}

Brief review: Metrics, traces, and logs consistently point to a throughput collapse (large relative drops in trace row_count and log.row_count) affecting many callers into ts-order-service starting around 2024-01-23 12:27:00 UTC. Concurrent metric anomalies on ts-order-service show elevated memory and disk-IO/socket signals. Traces show the most severe and widespread row_count drops are calls into ts-order-service from many services. Therefore the most likely root cause is ts-order-service experiencing resource pressure, with high memory usage the primary proximate reason.

